Statistics Project 2¶

Maria Molodova¶

Dataset description¶

MASS (version 7.3-58.1)

Boston: Housing Values in Suburbs of Boston¶

The Boston data frame has 506 rows and 14 columns.

The data frame contains the following columns:

  • crim

per capita crime rate by town.

  • zn

proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.

  • indus

proportion of non-retail business acres per town.

  • chas

Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).

  • nox

nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).

  • rm

average number of rooms per dwelling.

  • age

proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.

  • dis

weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.

  • rad

index of accessibility to radial highways.

  • tax

full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.

  • ptratio

pupil-teacher ratio by town.

  • black

1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.

  • lstat

lower status of the population (percent).

  • medv

median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

Part 2 - Model evaluation¶

a. Check for linearity¶

When considering a simple linear regression model, it is important to check the linearity assumption - i.e., that the conditional means of the response variable are a linear function of the predictor variable. Graphing the response variable vs the predictor can often give a good idea of whether or not this is true.

d. Check for Normality and Equal Variance¶

Check for Normality or Other Distribution

Let's use a Q-Q plot and a histogram (although a less robust way) to check out the residuals distribution

In [22]:
fig = sm.qqplot(resid_full, fit=True, line="45");
plt.show();
In [23]:
sns.histplot(resid_full);

The distribution is close to normal, although the right tail is longer, indicating underestimation by the model.

Equal Variance:

We have already plotted residuals against fitted values (in most cases, these are the estimated conditional means, according to the model). From the plot, we can assume equality of variance (since conditional variances usually depend on conditional means, especially tending to increase as conditional means increase) .

In [ ]:
def calculate_vif(X):
    vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
    vif_data["feature"] = X.columns
    vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i)
                            for i in range(len(X.columns))]

    return vif_data
